------ Quotes follow -----

From "The REXX Language", p. 17:
> Symbols are groups of any characters, selected from the alphabetic and
> numeric characters (A--Z, a--z, 0--9) and/or from the national
> currency symbols (including the symbols for dollar, cent, and pound-
> sterling) and/or from the characters @ [commercial at] # [number sign]
> . ! [exclamation mark] ? and underscore. [...]
> These are valid symbols:
>    [...]
>    HI!
> [...] A symbol may be a constant (such as a number), a keyword, or the
> name of a variable.

From "The REXX Language", p. 27--28:
> When used as a term in an expression (rather than as a keyword of some
> kind, for example), symbols may be subdivided into four groups: con-
> stant symbols, simple symbols, compound symbols, and stems. [...]
> Simple symbols may be used for variables where the name corresponds to
> a single value. [...]
>
> Simple symbols
>   The symbol itself does not contain any periods, and does not start
>   with a digit (0--9). [...]
>   These are simple symbols:
>     [...]
>     Whatagoodidea!

From "The REXX Language", 2nd edition, p. 21:
> Symbols are groups of any characters, selected from the English alpha-
> betic and numeric characters (A--Z, a--z, 0--9) and/or from the
> characters . ! [exclamation mark] ? and underscore.
> [Footnote:] Implementations may also informally allow characters such
> as national currency symbols (including the symbols for dollar, cent,
> and pound-sterling), accented and other language-specific characters,
> or the characters @ [commercial at] or # [number sign]. [...]
> [End of Footnote] [...]
> Examples:
>    [...]
>    HI!
> [...] A symbol may be a constant (such as a number), e keyword, or the
> name of a variable.

"The REXX Language", p. 32--33, matches, verbatim, the text from the 1st
edition, p. 27--28, quoted above.

The ANSI X3J18 REXX Standards Committee has twice discussed this issue,
as follows.

From X3J18 6th meeting's discussion notes (29 Sep 1992):
> Character Sets
> [...]
> There was some discussion concerning the characters what can be used to
> form a symbol. TRL2 has removed the national currency characters from
> this set, as "ambiguous" and therefore detrimental to portability. Yet
> there was support among the committee for inclusion of foreign
> alphabetic characters in symbols.

From X3J18 10th meeting's discussion notes (11 Oct 1993):
> Miscellaneous points discussed:
> [...]
> We agreed to reserve a portion of the symbol name space for use by
> future standards in the extension of the language. In this standard, no
> symbols (other than valid numeric constants) may begin with the
> character ".". It is intended that in a future standard symbols which
> begin with a period may be used in place of the special variables (such
> as RC and RESULT) currently used in the language.
>
> Similarly, we agreed to reserve a portion of the function name space
> as well, in that no function name may end with the character ".".
> The intent here is to allow for a future extension supporting
> expressions as stem tails, such as ABC.(J+1)


From the X3J18 11th meeting's discussion notes (28 Dec 1993):
> With respect to the "not" character, the committee agreed that
> requiring single "not" character within the standard when most existing
> programs do not use the chosen character is not a good idea. We agreed
> that the standard would require "\" as a "not" character, but would
> allow "^" and the EBCDIC "not" character (i.e., the "fallen L") as
> acceptable additional "not" characters, in a manner similar to the
> "extra blank" character concept that was introduced to handle the
> extended whitespace characters found in the more modern computing
> environments.

